---

<IndividualPageLayout
    title={seoTitle}
    description={seoDescription}
    schema={pageSchema}
    pageTitle={pageTitle}
    heroImage="/oscar/media/titanium-investment-casting-lost-wax-process-hero.webp"
    heroImageAlt="Titanium investment casting hero image showing a finished precision cast component, ceramic shell tree, and molten metal pouring in a modern foundry"
    faqSectionTitle="Frequently Asked Questions: Investment Casting"
    faqItems={faqs}
    ctaTitle="Request Quote For Investment Casting"
    ctaDescription=""
    sourcesTitle="Sources"
    sourcesList={sources}
    resourcesTitle="Our Internal Resources for Die Casting, Investment casting, Forging and Sand Casting"
    resourcesList={internalResources}
>

    <div slot="full-width" class="individual-content">

        <section id="overview" >
            <div class="content-container">
                
                <h2>Investment Casting (Lost-Wax Process): High-Precision, Near-Net-Shape Manufacturing</h2>

                <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-2 lg:items-center mt-6">
                    <div>
                        <p>
                           ForceBeyond is a premier global supplier of high-precision investment casting components. Also known as the lost-wax process, investment 
                           casting is the ultimate manufacturing solution for producing highly intricate, near-net-shape metal parts with exceptional surface 
                           finishes and tight dimensional tolerances.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Operating under a strict ISO 9001:2015 quality management system, our dual-shore manufacturing network delivers mission-critical 
                            investment castings to the aerospace, medical, energy, and fluid control sectors. Whether you require standard carbon steel 
                            brackets or vacuum-cast Inconel 718 turbine blades, 
                            ForceBeyond has the scalable capacity to produce complex castings weighing from a fraction of an ounce up to over 200 pounds.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="relative">
                        <div class="overflow-hidden">
                            <img
                                src="/oscar/media/custom-investment-casting-parts-valves-fittings-housings-4k.webp"
                                alt="Custom investment-cast metal parts, including valve bodies, threaded fittings, flanges, housings, and industrial pipe components, on a white background."
                                class="w-full h-auto object-cover hover:scale-105 transition-transform duration-500"
                            />
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="technical-capabilities" >
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Technical Capabilities: Investment Casting Materials</h2>
                    <p>
                        The investment casting process is highly versatile, allowing for the pouring of almost any ferrous or non-ferrous alloy. 
                        ForceBeyond specializes in high-performance metallurgy, 
                        utilizing both standard air-melt and advanced Vacuum Induction Melting (VIM) technologies.
                    </p>
                    <div class="content-table-wrapper">
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="col">Material Category</th>
                                <th scope="col">Core Alloys Poured</th>
                                <th scope="col">Key Features & Optimal Applications</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>

                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Stainless & Duplex Steel</th>
                                <td>304, 316L, 17-4 PH, 2205 Duplex</td>
                                <td>Superior corrosion resistance and hygiene. Ideal for medical instruments, marine hardware, and high-pressure fluid valves.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Superalloys (VIM)</th>
                                <td>Inconel 718, Inconel 625, Hastelloy</td>
                                <td>Extreme heat and fatigue resistance. Critical for aerospace engine components and industrial gas turbines.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Titanium</th>
                                <td>Ti-6Al-4V (Grade 5)</td>
                                <td>Unmatched strength-to-weight ratio. Used heavily in aerospace structural parts and biocompatible medical implants.</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <th scope="row">Carbon & Low-Alloy Steel</th>
                                <td>1020, 1045, 4140, 8620</td>
                                <td>Excellent strength and toughness. Widely used for heavy machinery, automotive components, and industrial brackets.</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div> 
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="why-forcebeyond" >
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Why Partner with ForceBeyond for Investment Casting?</h2>
                
                <p>
                    When your engineering designs demand internal cavities, undercut geometries, and ultra-thin walls, 
                    investment casting frequently outperforms sand casting, forging, and CNC machining from billet.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Unrestricted Design Freedom:</strong>Because the ceramic shell is built around a sacrificial wax pattern that is melted away, there is no need for draft angles or split-line constraints. You can cast highly complex internal coring and intricate features that are impossible to machine.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Near-Net-Shape Accuracy:</strong>Investment casting routinely achieves tight standard tolerances (typically ISO 8062 CT5 to CT7). This dramatically reduces—and often completely eliminates—the need for secondary CNC machining, saving significant time and material costs.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Superior Surface Finish:</strong>: The fine ceramic slurry used to coat the wax pattern yields a remarkably smooth as-cast surface finish (typically 125 RMS or better), ideal for parts requiring aesthetic appeal or immediate plating.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Zero Material Waste on Exotic Alloys:</strong>Machining a part from a solid block of Titanium or Inconel wastes highly expensive raw material. Investment casting pours metal directly into the exact shape of your part, ensuring maximum material yield.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                
            </div>
        </section>
        <section id="investment-casting-process">
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>
                    The Investment Casting Process
                </h2>
                <p>
                    ForceBeyond utilizes state-of-the-art robotic shelling and automated wax injection to ensure repeatable lot-to-lot consistency.
                </p>
                <ul class="no-bullets">
                    <li>
                        <strong>1.Wax Injection & Assembly:</strong> Precision aluminum dies are used to inject sacrificial wax patterns, which are then assembled onto a central wax sprue (a "tree").
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>2.Ceramic Shelling:</strong> The wax tree is repeatedly dipped into a fine ceramic slurry and coated with refractory sand to build a strong, heat-resistant shell.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>3.Dewaxing & Firing</strong> The shell is heated in an autoclave to melt out the wax (hence, "lost-wax"), leaving a hollow cavity that perfectly matches the part design. The shell is then fired to increase its strength.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>4.Pouring & Knockout:</strong> Molten alloy is poured into the hot ceramic shell. Once solidified, the ceramic is broken away (knocked out), and the individual castings are cut from the central sprue.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id = "Tier-1.5-integration">
            <div class="content-container">
                <h2>Tier-1.5 Integration: Cast-to-Machine Solutions</h2>
                <p>
                    While investment casting reduces machining requirements, tight engineering tolerances often require precision finishing. 
                    ForceBeyond operates a Tier-1.5 model, keeping all secondary operations in-house to eliminate dimensional hand-off risks between vendors.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Precision CNC Machining:</strong>5-axis milling, drilling, threading, and tapping of critical datum features.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Advanced Heat Treatment:</strong>Solution annealing, aging, and Hot Isostatic Pressing (HIP) to eliminate any internal microporosity and maximize fatigue life.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Rigorous NDT (Non-Destructive Testing):</strong>100% X-ray (Radiographic Testing) to verify internal integrity, alongside Fluorescent Penetrant Inspection (FPI) for surface defect detection.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Surface Finishing:</strong>Electropolishing, passivation (critical for stainless steel), and bead blasting.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
</IndividualPageLayout>